</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0001">1</a>
	
   <p>Schuyler is replying to <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0557" class="document">GWs letter to him of 24 December</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0002">2</a>
	
   <p>Schuyler expressed his desire to retire from the army in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0383" class="document">his letter to GW of 22 Nov. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>GW requested information regarding Richard Prescotts treatment of Ethan Allan in his letter to Schuyler of 18 December. For Prescotts capture by the Americans in Canada, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0409&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-02-02-0409-fn-0002#GEWN-03-02-02-0409-fn-0002" class="document">Schuyler to GW, 28 Nov. 1775, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Two soldiers told Eleazar Wheelock that Robert Rogers had been second
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0035">[35]</span>
in command under Guy Carleton at St. Jean the previous fall (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0429" class="document">Wheelock to GW, 2 Dec.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0531" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 18 Dec. 1775</a>). For Rogerss passes, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0505&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-02-02-0505-fn-0002#GEWN-03-02-02-0505-fn-0002" class="document">Rogers to GW, 14 Dec. 1775, n.2.</a></p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0005">5</a>
	
   <p>GW enclosed the account against Daniel Morgan in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0531" class="document">his letter to Schuyler of 18 December</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>Schuyler enclosed a copy of the letter that Richard Montgomery sent to him from Holland House . . . Near the Heights of Abraham on 5 December. The Season, Montgomery wrote, has proved so favourable as to enable me to join Colonel Arnold at Point Aux Trembles, where I arrived with the Vessels Mr [Richard] Prescott made us a Present of, they carried the few Troops about 300 which were equipped for a Winter Campaign, with the Artillery &amp;caColonel [James] Livingston is on his Way with some part of his Regiment of Canadians. Mr [Guy] Carleton who is I suppose ashamed to shew himself in England, is now in Town &amp; puts on the shew of Defence. . . . I propose Amuzing Mr Carleton with a formal Attack erecting Batteries &amp;ca but mean to insult the Works, I believe towards the lower Town, Which is the weakest Part[.] I have this Day written to Mr Carleton &amp; also to the Inhabitants which I hope will have some Effect, I shall be very sorry to be reduced to this Mode of Attack, because I know the Melancholly Consequences, But the approaching severe season &amp; the Weakness of the Garrison together with the Nature of the Works point It out too strongly to be passed by (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). For the failure of the American attack on Quebec and Montgomerys death, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0056" class="document">Schuyler to GW, 13 January</a>. Schuyler also enclosed a copy of David Woosters letter to him of 18 Dec. 1775 (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0079&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0079-fn-0005#GEWN-03-03-02-0079-fn-0005" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 16 Jan. 1776, n.5</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0007">7</a>
	
   <p>For another account of the artillery from Ticonderoga, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0019" class="document">Henry Knox to GW, this date</a>. The previous Wednesday was 3 January.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0008">8</a>
	
   <p>This party included Colonel Louis, the chief who had visited GW the previous summer (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0150&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-01-02-0150-fn-0032#GEWN-03-01-02-0150-fn-0032" class="document">GW to Hancock, 45 Aug. 1775, n.32</a>). The Caughnawaga, who had recently signed a treaty of neutrality with Schuyler, arrived at Cambridge on 20 Jan. and held a formal talk with GW ten days later (see GW to Hancock, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0127" class="document">24</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0157" class="document">30 Jan.</a>, and GW to Schuyler, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0145" class="document">27 Jan.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0173" class="document">1 Feb.</a> 1776). The escorting officer may have been Nathaniel Wales, quartermaster of Col. Timothy Bedels New Hampshire regiment.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0009">9</a>
	
   <p>GW enclosed copies of <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0529" class="document">his letter to Howe of 18 Dec.</a> concerning the treatment of Ethan Allan and Howes reply of 21 Dec. in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0557" class="document">his letter to Schuyler of 24 December</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0010">10</a>
	
   <p>GW requested this clothing in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0557" class="document">his letter to Schuyler of 24 December</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0011-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0021-fn-0011">11</a>

   <p>Thomas Gamble, a captain in the 47th Regiment who had served as an assistant deputy quartermaster general in America since 1766, was captured with Richard Prescott at Lavaltrie in November 1775 while trying to escape from Montreal to Quebec. The Americans had intercepted letters from Gamble to Thomas Gage and William Shirreff the previous September (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0094&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-02-02-0094-fn-0003#GEWN-03-02-02-0094-fn-0003" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 4 Oct. 1775, n.3</a>). For GWs refusal to parole or exchange Gamble under existing circumstances, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0079" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 16 January</a>. Congress rejected Gambles appeal for exchange in April, and in July he was imprisoned for ill behavior (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:264, 5:567). Gamble was exchanged in November or December 1776. He was recaptured at Princeton in January 1777 and apparently
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0036">[36]</span>
was released again soon afterwards (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-08-02-0173&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-08-02-0173-fn-0003#GEWN-03-08-02-0173-fn-0003" class="document">Gamble to GW, 22 Jan. 1777</a>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ New York Public Library, New York ]">NN</span>: Schuyler Papers, and 17 Feb. 1777, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
